From 96298b16269a3baf5919c6ff8f844e2b53bbb7cf Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Ilya Gulya <ilya@gulya.me>
Date: Sun, 28 Jun 2026 08:15:52 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] darlingserver: NO_REPLY fire-and-forget RPC class for pure
 setters (perf #10)

The per-call RPC profile (perf #9, dar-dar6x4-perf-5dq.16) showed ~40% of build RPCs
are once-per-process startup calls, and several are pure SETTERS with an EMPTY reply
(set_dyld_info, set_executable_path, ...). Each still pays a full synchronous round-
trip: send + a ~200us recvmsg sleep, only to read a status code the guest discards.
That reply-wait sleep is the 57% of guest build wall-clock the profile (perf #6) found.

Add a NO_REPLY rpc flag. For a NO_REPLY call:
  - the generated client wrapper sends the request and returns 0 IMMEDIATELY, skipping
    the entire receive/decode block (that skipped recvmsg sleep is the win);
  - the server-side _sendReply is generated as a no-op, so the server emits NO reply
    datagram (a stray reply would land in the per-thread socket buffer and desync the
    next synchronous call's reply matching). processCall() still runs the work.
Ordering is preserved: per-thread datagrams are processed in send order, so a NO_REPLY
setter is always applied before any later synchronous call that depends on its effect.

Applied to set_dyld_info + set_executable_path (mldr-side, pure crash-report/introspect
metadata nothing on the startup critical path reads back). set_thread_handles was tried
but reverted -- early pthread init is sensitive; left synchronous.

IMPORTANT build note: mldr STATICALLY links the generated RPC wrappers (mldr_dserver_rpc
from rpc.c), so a NO_REPLY change requires rebuilding mldr too -- otherwise a stale mldr
keeps waiting for a reply the new server no longer sends and the guest hangs in recvmsg
at launchd startup (no shellspawn). All three consumers (mldr, libsystem_kernel, server)
must be rebuilt together.

Validated: full matched set boots (shellspawn up) and a real make -j8 build completes
500/500; set_dyld_info/set_executable_path no longer block the guest on a reply.

RED->GREEN test committed alongside (standing TDD rule): no_reply_rpc_test.sh runs the
generator and asserts a NO_REPLY call's wrapper omits receive_message and its server
_sendReply is a no-op, while a normal call (checkin) still receives. Proven RED before
the flag existed.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
